{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631520"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:28:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:28:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17379"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17379"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10069"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115110"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10069"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97118"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7769"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23575"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115110"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is studying the relationship between duration of physiotherapy and improvement in knee range of motion following total knee replacement. The scatter plot shows a clear upward trend with points clustered fairly closely around an imaginary straight line.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the likely Pearson correlation coefficient for this relationship?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["-0.8","+0.8","0","-0.2","+0.2"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe scenario describes a strong positive linear relationship between physiotherapy duration and knee range of motion improvement. A \u003Cstrong\u003E+0.8\u003C/strong\u003E correlation coefficient indicates this strong positive association, where as treatment time increases, mobility tends to increase in a fairly predictable way.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E-0.8\u003C/strong\u003E indicates a strong negative correlation, which would show a downward trend with mobility decreasing as treatment duration increases. \u003Cstrong\u003E+0.2\u003C/strong\u003E indicates a weak positive correlation, which would show a much more scattered pattern with minimal predictive value. \u003Cstrong\u003E0\u003C/strong\u003E indicates no linear relationship between variables, suggesting treatment has no consistent effect on mobility improvement. \u003Cstrong\u003E-0.2\u003C/strong\u003E indicates a weak negative correlation, which would show a slightly downward but very scattered trend.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Pearson correlation coefficient ranges from -1 (perfect negative correlation) through 0 (no correlation) to +1 (perfect positive correlation). Values around \u00b10.8 indicate strong correlation, \u00b10.5 indicate moderate correlation, and \u00b10.2 indicate weak correlation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pearson correlation coefficient (r) quantifies the linear relationship between two continuous variables on a scale from -1 to +1.","Strong positive correlations (r \u2248 +0.8) indicate that as one variable increases, the other tends to increase proportionally.","Clinical research often uses Pearson correlation to assess relationships between treatment duration and symptom improvement."],"references":["Motulsky H. Intuitive Biostatistics: A Nonmathematical Guide to Statistical Thinking. 4th ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press; 2017. Chapter 41; pg. 434","Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97118"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17379"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97118"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T11:41:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T11:41:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10069"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115110"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T2